The coefficient $a_k=\begin{align}\binom{50}{k}3^{50-k}\end{align}$ has non-decreasing behavior with respect to $k$ until $k+1$ as shown below
\begin{align*}
\frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}&=\frac{\begin{align}\binom{50}{k+1}3^{50-k-1}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\binom{50}{k}3^{50-k}\end{align}}\\[2pt]
&=\frac{\begin{align}\frac{50!}{(k+1)!(50-(k+1))!}3^{50-k-1}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\frac{50!}{k!(50-k)!}3^{50-k}\end{align}}\\[2pt]
&=\frac{\begin{align}\frac{1}{k+1}\frac{1}{(50-k)}3^{50-k-1}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\frac{1}{1}\frac{1}{1}3^{50-k}\end{align}}\\[2pt]
&=\frac{\begin{align}\frac{1}{k+1}(50-k)\frac{1}{3}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\frac{1}{1}\end{align}}\\[2pt]
&=\frac{\begin{align}\frac{50-k}{3}\end{align}}{\begin{align}k+1\end{align}}\\[2pt]
&<1\qquad\qquad 2\leq k\leq 49
\end{align*}
The coefficient $a_k$ thus increases with increasing $k$ until $k^{\ast}$ such that
\begin{align*}
a_{k^{\ast}}\geq a_{k^{\ast}+1}\quad\text{ or equivalently }3(k^{\ast}+1)\geq 50-k^{\ast}.
\end{align*}
Thus we obtain $k^{\ast}\geq 8$. arguably $k^{\ast}=9$ because
\begin{align*}
a_9=\frac{\binom{50}{9}3^{41}\times\color{green}{50}}{10\tag{$\star$}}
\end{align*}
is maximized.
The same could have been deduced by also observing the coefficient $a_k$ decreases with increasing $k$ until $k^{\ast}$ as shown below
\begin{align*}
\frac{a_k}{a_{k+1}}=\frac{\begin{align}\binom{50}{k}3^{50-k}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\binom{50}{k+1}3^{50-k-1}\end{align}}=\frac{\begin{align}\frac{50!}{k!(50-k)!}\end{align}}{\begin{align}\frac{50!}{(k+1)!(50-(k+1))!}\end{align}}=\color{blue}{\frac{1}{1}\frac{1}{50-k}\color{green}{3}}=(50-k)/3\,.
\end{align*}
Thus the ratio $a_k/a_{k+1}$ maximizes at $k^*$.</answer>

